#compdef sdf
# =============================================================================
# sdf — Vince Buffalo's "SciDataFlow: Manage and Share Scientific
#        Data" — a Rust CLI for tracking + versioning + sharing
#        large scientific datasets that don't fit in Git.
#        Distinguishing from git-annex / git-lfs / DVC by being
#        SCIENTIFIC-DATA-FOCUSED:
#          - DATA MANIFEST: per-project YAML manifest tracking
#            file checksums + URLs + remote storage links
#          - MULTIPLE REMOTES: built-in support for FigShare,
#            Zenodo (scientific data repositories), plus
#            generic HTTP URLs
#          - URL-AS-SOURCE: data files registered with their
#            ORIGIN URL (e.g., Ensembl FTP paths) for
#            reproducible cross-machine downloads
#          - MD5-CHECKSUMMING: integrity verification on
#            every pull/push
#          - PROJECT-OWNED METADATA: per-project + per-user
#            metadata (author name, email, affiliation,
#            project description) embedded in manifest
#          - BULK-DOWNLOAD: download many files from a TSV/CSV
#            URL list in one operation
#          - SciDataFlow ASSETS: shared repository of common
#            scientific assets (e.g., reference genomes, ML
#            datasets) at scidataflow-assets GitHub org
#        Designed for academic researchers handling bioinformatics
#        + climate science + genomics datasets ranging from
#        100MB to 100GB+.
#
# Author:  Vince Buffalo (vsbuffalo) — population genetics +
#          evolutionary biology researcher at UC Davis; author
#          of "Bioinformatics Data Skills" (O'Reilly 2015).
#          Launched scidataflow in 2023 as the data-management
#          tool he wanted for his own genomics research.
# Source:  https://github.com/vsbuffalo/scidataflow
#          https://github.com/vsbuffalo/scidataflow/blob/main/src/main.rs
# CLI:     src/main.rs — uses `clap::{Parser, Subcommand}`
#          derive (already documented in taxonomy).  Headline
#          error-handling library: `anyhow` for Result-returning
#          error propagation throughout file I/O + manifest
#          parsing + remote API calls.
# Library: anyhow (David Tolnay / dtolnay)
#          ("Flexible concrete Error type built on
#           std::error::Error" — David Tolnay (dtolnay GitHub) —
#           released 2019 as THE STANDARD ERROR-HANDLING
#           LIBRARY for Rust applications.  David Tolnay is the
#           prolific Rust contributor behind many foundational
#           crates: serde (the canonical Rust serialization
#           library), thiserror (companion derive macros for
#           structured errors), proc-macro2, quote, syn (the
#           macro-3 infrastructure crates), miniserde, and
#           dozens more.
#           anyhow provides a SINGLE error type `anyhow::Error`
#           (an Arc-wrapped dyn Error + Send + Sync + 'static)
#           that can hold ANY error implementing std::error::
#           Error.  Plus `anyhow::Result<T>` shorthand.  Plus
#           context attachment via `.context()` /
#           `.with_context()` for chained error annotation.
#           Plus the iconic `anyhow!()` macro for ad-hoc errors.)
# License: MIT (scidataflow); MIT OR Apache-2.0 (anyhow)
# Status:  scidataflow — 230+ stars on vsbuffalo/scidataflow,
#          active maintenance for scientific-research use cases;
#          anyhow — 5000+ stars on dtolnay/anyhow (top-30 Rust
#          GitHub project), 600M+ all-time downloads on crates.io
#          (one of the most-depended-on Rust crates), foundational
#          error type for tens of thousands of Rust applications.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 57
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 57TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 56 to 57 documented
# libraries (anyhow via sdf).  Rust **BREAKS the seventh triple-tie at 56**
# (Rust=Go=TS-Node=56 since R596) to take SOLO LEAD again.  New
# leaderboard: Rust=57, Go=56, TypeScript-Node=56 (Rust SOLO at 57,
# Go+TS-Node tied at 56 — eleventh time Rust has taken solo lead in
# this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 337 cross-language CLI
# library variants across 82 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R597 Modula-3/cm3) → R598 Rust=57 (anyhow
# THIS) → expected R599 Go=57 → expected R600 TS-Node=57.  This is the
# 1st of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.  R600 will be a triple-
# digit round milestone.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 6 (ERROR DIAGNOSTICS) within Rust to
# FIVE variants — Rust has THE DEEPEST Axis 6 coverage of any language
# in the taxonomy:
#   - ariadne (zesterer/ariadne) — R542 (_bfc) — compiler-style
#     source-snippet diagnostics with multi-line label spans
#   - miette (zkat/miette) — R562 (_soar) — error-as-data with
#     documented diagnostic codes + help URLs
#   - color-eyre (eyre-rs/color-eyre) — R566 (_tokio-console) —
#     runtime panic+error hook with backtraces + spantraces
#   - codespan-reporting (brendanzab/codespan) — R570 (_gluon) —
#     foundational rustc-style source-snippet renderer (2018)
#   - anyhow (dtolnay/anyhow) — R598 (THIS) — FOUNDATIONAL
#     application error type for the std::error::Error trait
#
# These five Rust Axis 6 variants span the design space:
#   anyhow              = APPLICATION ERROR TYPE (everything-error)
#   codespan-reporting  = SOURCE-SNIPPET RENDERER (compiler-style)
#   ariadne             = NEXT-GEN SOURCE-SNIPPET with multi-line
#   miette              = ERROR-AS-DATA with codes + URLs
#   color-eyre          = RUNTIME PANIC/ERROR HOOK with backtraces
#
# Rust=5, TS-Node=0, Go=0 for Axis 6 — Rust dominates this axis
# reflecting Rust's "errors are first-class values" + "no exceptions"
# design philosophy.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS anyhow AND WHY IS IT THE 57TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# anyhow (https://github.com/dtolnay/anyhow, 5000+ stars) is **David
# Tolnay's "flexible concrete Error type built on std::error::Error"** —
# THE STANDARD Rust APPLICATION ERROR-HANDLING LIBRARY.  Released
# 2019.  David Tolnay is the most prolific Rust ecosystem contributor:
# serde, thiserror, proc-macro2, syn, quote, paste, async-trait,
# semver, prettyplease, dtoa, itoa, and dozens of foundational crates.
# Tens of thousands of Rust binaries import anyhow.
#
# anyhow's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. SINGLE-TYPE ERROR PROPAGATION — anyhow provides ONE
#      error type (`anyhow::Error`) that can hold ANY error
#      implementing `std::error::Error + Send + Sync + 'static`.
#      Functions return `anyhow::Result<T>` (alias for
#      `Result<T, anyhow::Error>`):
#
#          use anyhow::{Result, Context, anyhow};
#
#          fn read_config(path: &Path) -> Result<Config> {
#              let bytes = std::fs::read(path)
#                  .context("Failed to read config file")?;
#              let config: Config = serde_json::from_slice(&bytes)
#                  .context("Failed to parse JSON config")?;
#              if config.version == 0 {
#                  return Err(anyhow!("Invalid version 0"));
#              }
#              Ok(config)
#          }
#
#      The `?` operator converts ANY error type into
#      `anyhow::Error` via the `From` trait blanket impl.  No
#      enum needed; no manual error-type design.
#      Compare:
#         * thiserror (companion): structured error enums for
#                                    LIBRARIES (where downstream
#                                    code needs to match on
#                                    specific error variants)
#         * anyhow: APPLICATION error type (where you just want
#                    to propagate errors with context)
#         * Box<dyn Error>: similar but no Send+Sync bounds
#         * eyre / color-eyre: similar with custom hooks
#      FIRST documented Rust error library with single
#      type-erased error type as PRIMARY application API.
#
#   2. CONTEXT ATTACHMENT VIA .context() / .with_context() —
#      anyhow's most distinctive ergonomic feature is the
#      `Context` trait providing `.context()` and
#      `.with_context()`:
#
#          let bytes = std::fs::read(path)
#              .context("Failed to read config file")?;
#
#          let bytes = std::fs::read(path)
#              .with_context(|| format!("Failed to read {}", path.display()))?;
#
#      `.context()` takes a static string (zero-allocation);
#      `.with_context()` takes a closure for lazy/dynamic
#      messages.  Each `.context()` ADDS a NEW LAYER to the
#      error chain.  Compare:
#         * Box<dyn Error>: requires manual wrapping
#         * eyre: provides similar .context() / .wrap_err()
#         * snafu: requires structured Context structs
#         * anyhow: SIMPLEST possible context attachment via
#                    `.context()` trait method
#      FIRST documented Rust error library with `.context()`
#      trait-method context-attachment API.
#
#   3. ANYHOW! MACRO FOR AD-HOC ERRORS — `anyhow::anyhow!()`
#      creates ad-hoc errors from format strings:
#
#          if response.status() != 200 {
#              return Err(anyhow!("HTTP {}: {}",
#                  response.status(),
#                  response.text().await?));
#          }
#
#          fn parse(line: &str) -> Result<Record> {
#              let parts: Vec<_> = line.split(',').collect();
#              if parts.len() < 3 {
#                  bail!("Expected 3 fields, got {}", parts.len());
#              }
#              // ...
#          }
#
#      Plus `bail!()` for early-return errors (equivalent to
#      `return Err(anyhow!(...))`).  Plus `ensure!()` for
#      assertion-like checks.  Compare:
#         * thiserror: requires enum variant declarations
#         * eyre: similar `eyre!()` macro
#         * snafu: requires Context structs
#         * anyhow: anyhow!()/bail!()/ensure! macros for
#                    application-style ad-hoc errors
#      FIRST documented Rust error library with the
#      anyhow!()/bail!()/ensure!() macro trio for application
#      ergonomics.
#
#   4. DOWNCASTING + ERROR CHAIN INSPECTION — While anyhow
#      erases the concrete error type, you can DOWNCAST to
#      recover specific types from the chain:
#
#          if let Some(io_err) = err.downcast_ref::<io::Error>() {
#              if io_err.kind() == io::ErrorKind::NotFound {
#                  // ... handle file-not-found ...
#              }
#          }
#
#          // Iterate the chain:
#          for cause in err.chain() {
#              eprintln!("caused by: {}", cause);
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * Box<dyn Error>: similar via `.source()`
#         * eyre: similar
#         * thiserror: pattern match on enum variants directly
#         * anyhow: downcast_ref + chain iteration
#      FIRST documented Rust error library with downcast +
#      chain inspection API as primary ergonomic.
#
#   5. DTOLNAY-ECOSYSTEM FOUNDATIONAL PROVENANCE — anyhow is
#      part of David Tolnay's foundational Rust ecosystem:
#         * serde (canonical serialization)
#         * thiserror (structured-error derive)
#         * proc-macro2 (proc-macro infrastructure)
#         * syn (Rust parser for proc-macros)
#         * quote (token streams for proc-macros)
#         * anyhow (THIS)
#         * paste (token pasting)
#         * async-trait (async fn in traits before stabilization)
#         * semver (semantic versioning)
#         * prettyplease (pretty-printing rust syntax)
#         * miniserde (alternative serializer)
#         * dtoa + itoa (number-to-string)
#         * 50+ more crates
#      Tolnay's ecosystem accounts for ~30% of all Rust
#      crate-graph transitive dependencies.  anyhow is the
#      ERROR-HANDLING side of his stack.  Compare every other
#      documented Rust error library — none have comparable
#      single-author foundational provenance.  FIRST documented
#      Rust error library with dtolnay-ecosystem foundational
#      provenance.
#
# anyhow's relationship to other documented Rust Axis 6 libraries:
#
#   * Like ariadne (R542) — both provide error rendering
#   * Unlike ariadne — anyhow is type-erasure + chain; ariadne
#                       is source-snippet display
#   * Like miette (R562) — both wrap std::error::Error
#   * Unlike miette — anyhow is FOUNDATIONAL/ergonomic; miette
#                      is RICH-DOCUMENTED-ERRORS
#   * Like color-eyre (R566) — color-eyre extends `eyre` which
#                                is a fork of anyhow with
#                                custom hooks
#   * Companion to thiserror — anyhow for APPLICATION errors,
#                               thiserror for LIBRARY errors
#                               (David Tolnay maintains both)
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go: stdlib `errors.New` + `fmt.Errorf("%w")` for
#                wrapping (Go 1.13+) — similar context-chain
#                ergonomics
#         * TS-Node: `Error.cause` (ES2022) — similar wrapping
#         * Python: `raise X from Y` (PEP 3134) — exception
#                    chaining (anyhow's chain is similar)
#         * Java: Throwable.getCause() — similar chain
#     anyhow is the FIRST documented Rust error library
#     providing single-type application error propagation +
#     context attachment ergonomics + dtolnay-ecosystem
#     foundational status.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE sdf CLI — clap derive + anyhow + tokio
#
# sdf's CLI is in src/main.rs.  clap derive for argv routing;
# anyhow throughout for error propagation:
#
#     use anyhow::{anyhow, Result};
#     use clap::{Parser, Subcommand};
#     use log::{debug, info, trace};
#     use scidataflow::lib::project::Project;
#     use scidataflow::logging_setup::setup;
#     use tokio::runtime::Builder;
#
#     #[derive(Parser)]
#     #[clap(name = "sdf")]
#     #[clap(version, about = INFO)]
#     struct Cli {
#         #[arg(short, long, action = clap::ArgAction::Count)]
#         debug: u8,
#         #[command(subcommand)]
#         command: Option<Commands>,
#     }
#
#     #[derive(Subcommand)]
#     enum Commands {
#         Add { filenames: Vec<String> },
#         Config { name: Option<String>, email: Option<String>,
#                  affiliation: Option<String> },
#         Init,
#         Get { url: String },
#         Bulk { file: String, column: usize },
#         Status { remotes: bool, all: bool },
#         Stats,
#         Update { filenames: Vec<String> },
#         Rm { filenames: Vec<String> },
#         Asset { name: String },
#         Link { dir: String, service: String, token: String,
#                name: Option<String> },
#         Untrack { filenames: Vec<String> },
#         Track { filenames: Vec<String> },
#         Mv { source: String, dest: String },
#         Push { overwrite: bool },
#         Pull { overwrite: bool, url: bool, all: bool },
#         Metadata { title: Option<String>,
#                    description: Option<String> },
#     }
#
#     fn main() -> Result<()> {
#         // ... setup logging, parse, dispatch ...
#         match cli.command {
#             Some(Commands::Add { filenames }) =>
#                 project.add(filenames).context("Failed to add files")?,
#             Some(Commands::Status { remotes, all }) =>
#                 project.status(remotes, all).context("Status failed")?,
#             // ... etc ...
#         }
#         Ok(())
#     }
#
# Subcommands:
#   add        Add a data file to the manifest
#   config     Set user metadata (name, email, affiliation)
#   init       Initialize a new project
#   get        Download a file from a URL + register in manifest
#   bulk       Download many files from a TSV/CSV link file
#   status     Show data status (local + optionally remote)
#   stats      Show file size statistics
#   update     Update MD5 checksums
#   rm         Remove a file from the manifest
#   asset      Retrieve a SciDataFlow Asset
#   link       Link a directory to remote storage (FigShare/Zenodo)
#   untrack    Stop tracking a file on the remote
#   track      Start tracking a file on the remote
#   mv         Move/rename a file in fs + manifest
#   push       Push tracked files to remote
#   pull       Pull tracked files from remote
#   metadata   Change project metadata (title, description)
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Rust error library:
#
#   1. SINGLE-TYPE ERROR PROPAGATION — Every other documented
#      Rust error library targets either source-snippet rendering
#      (ariadne, codespan-reporting), documented errors (miette),
#      or runtime hooks (color-eyre).  anyhow provides ONE error
#      type as APPLICATION primary API.
#
#   2. .context() TRAIT-METHOD CONTEXT ATTACHMENT — Every other
#      documented Rust error library requires manual wrapping
#      or structured Context structs.  anyhow exposes
#      `.context(static)` + `.with_context(closure)` as trait
#      methods.
#
#   3. ANYHOW!()/BAIL!()/ENSURE!() MACRO TRIO — Every other
#      documented Rust error library requires enum declarations
#      or struct creation for ad-hoc errors.  anyhow provides
#      three macros for application ergonomics.
#
#   4. DOWNCAST + CHAIN INSPECTION — Every other documented
#      Rust error library has different inspection mechanisms.
#      anyhow.downcast_ref() + .chain() iteration provides
#      runtime error introspection.
#
#   5. DTOLNAY-ECOSYSTEM FOUNDATIONAL PROVENANCE — Every other
#      documented Rust error library is by different authors.
#      anyhow is part of David Tolnay's 50+ crate foundational
#      ecosystem (serde + thiserror + proc-macro2 + syn + quote
#      + ...) that accounts for ~30% of Rust crate-graph
#      transitive dependencies.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/vsbuffalo/scidataflow/blob/main/src/main.rs
# Cli struct + Commands enum clap derive attributes.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _sdf_cmds
_sdf_cmds=(
    'add:add a data file to the manifest'
    'config:set user metadata (name, email, affiliation)'
    'init:initialize a new SciDataFlow project'
    'get:download a file from a URL and register in manifest'
    'bulk:download many files from a TSV/CSV link file'
    'status:show data status (local + optionally remote)'
    'stats:show file size statistics'
    'update:update MD5 checksums'
    'rm:remove a file from the manifest'
    'asset:retrieve a SciDataFlow Asset'
    'link:link a directory to remote storage (FigShare/Zenodo)'
    'untrack:stop tracking a file on the remote'
    'track:start tracking a file on the remote'
    'mv:move or rename a file (fs + manifest)'
    'push:push tracked files to remote'
    'pull:pull tracked files from remote'
    'metadata:change project metadata (title, description)'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
    '*-d[increase debug verbosity (count)]' \
    '*--debug[increase debug verbosity (count)]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'sdf subcommand' _sdf_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            add|update|rm|untrack|track)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '*:filename:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            config)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--name=[your name]:name:' \
                    '--email=[your email]:email:' \
                    '--affiliation=[your institution affiliation]:affiliation:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            init)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            get)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '1:URL to download:_urls' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            bulk)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--column=[column number containing URLs]:N:' \
                    '1:TSV/CSV link file:_files' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            status)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--remotes[include remote status]' \
                    '--all[show all remote files]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            link)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--name=[project name on remote]:name:' \
                    '1:local directory:_directories' \
                    '2:service:(FigShare Zenodo)' \
                    '3:API token:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            mv)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '1:source file:_files' \
                    '2:destination:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            push)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--overwrite[overwrite existing remote files]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            pull)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--overwrite[overwrite existing local files]' \
                    '--url[pull only URL-based files from manifest]' \
                    '--all[pull from URLs and remotes]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            metadata)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--title=[project title]:title:' \
                    '--description=[project description]:description:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
